{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17415667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17415667"},"attributes":{"position":58,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T09:13:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T09:13:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1620"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500190","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500190"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:10:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:10:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1620"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"1620","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1620"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.04,0.4,0.27,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1620"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46959"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1620","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1620"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1620"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31728"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"456"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2137"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31240"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/46959"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 43-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department after experiencing several episodes of right upper quadrant abdominal pain over the last three days. The pain is constant in nature and may last several minutes. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She immigrated from Turkey three years ago. On examination, her pulse rate is 79/min, blood pressure 120/80mmHg, and temperature 37.3\u00b0C. Her BMI is 31kg/m2. An abdominal ultrasound shows several small gallstones within the gallbladder and a smooth intrahepatic cyst. A follow-up abdominal CT is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following organisms is most likely responsible for the changes seen on the CT scan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Escherichia coli","Wuchereria bancrofti","Echinococcus granulosus","Entamoeba histolytica","Schistosoma haematobium"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere is a cystic lesion in segment 6 of the liver, adjacent to the gallbladder. The lining of the cyst is calcified, giving the characteristic appearance of an hydatid cyst. The organism responsible is \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EEchinococcus granulosus\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E. In areas of the world, where hydatid disease is endemic, man can often be the unwitting intermediate host. As such, the disease will often remain asymptomatic for years, only coming to attention as an incidental finding during an imaging investigation - such as in this patient with symptoms and imaging findings of cholelithiasis. Patients may become symptomatic when the cyst enlarges (\u0026gt;10 cm) or rupture. Symptomatic patients may present with mass effects (eg, right upper quadrant pain, nausea, vomiting, hepatomegaly).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003Cem\u003E \u003C/em\u003Eis not implicated in the development of a hydatid cyst. It may be a cause of cholecystitis due to secondary bacterial infection. However, this patient\u0027s clinical picture and ultrasound findings are inconsistent with the diagnosis of cholecystitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EWuchereria bancrofti\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E is implicated in the development of lymphatic filariasis. It presents with lymphoedema of the lower limbs. Liver involvement is not seen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EEntamoeba histolytica\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E may present with amoebic liver abscess. Patients typically present with fever and right upper quadrant pain. This patient is afebrile. Besides, eggshell calcifications (as seen in this patient) are not seen in patients with amoebic abscess.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ESchistosoma haematobium\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E presents with haematuria and dysuria. With chronic infection, these patients can develop squamous cell carcinoma of the bladder. Intrahepatic cysts are not a feature of schistosomiasis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Echinococcus granulosus causing hydatid disease will often remain asymptomatic for years, only coming to attention as an incidental finding during an imaging investigation."],"references":["Keong B, Wilkie B, Sutherland T, et al. Hepatic cystic echinococcosis in Australia: an update on diagnosis and management. ANZ J Surg 2018; 88:26-31."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31728"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1620"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14986"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14986"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/49277270-362d-44e1-bd84-105666a94ed1.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/49277270-362d-44e1-bd84-105666a94ed1.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":588,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31728"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-14T10:00:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-11T21:35:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1620"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46959"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},